# JS Tag Integration

Mula helps publishers increase engagement and monetize traffic through intelligent product recommendation widgets. This guide walks through how to install and customize Mula Web Tags on your site in under 10 minutes.

## Step 1 \- Install Mula Tag

Install the Mula script tag into the \<head\> of your site or via your Tag Manager:

\<script src="https://cdn.makemula.ai/js/mula.js" defer\>\</script\>

## Step 2 \- Decide on pages, widgets & placements.

1. Choose Your Widget Type and Placement  
   1. Start by selecting the widget you‚Äôd like to use \- our [TopShelf Carousel](#mula-topshelf-carousel) or [SmartScroll Feed](#mula-smartscroll-feed). We recommend beginning with SmartScroll, which performs best at the end of articles, and expanding to TopShelf for added monetization throughout your content.  
2. Next, work with the Mula team to identify consistent, high-impact placement locations on your article pages.  
   1. SmartScroll  
      1. Best placed at the end of articles for seamless engagement.  
   2. TopShelf  
      1. Highly flexible and can be embedded mid-article, below headlines, or wherever it fits your layout best.  
3. The Mula team will share demo links for your review and approval before launching on your site.

### Mula TopShelf Carousel {#mula-topshelf-carousel}

The TopShelf Carousel is a horizontal widget ideal for mid-article merchandising. It spans 100% of the container‚Äôs width and has a default height of 600px.  
![][image1]

### Mula SmartScroll Feed {#mula-smartscroll-feed}

The SmartScroll Feed is a vertical, ‚Äúinfinite-scroll‚Äù widget designed to drive engagement at the end of articles. It automatically surfaces contextually relevant products and spans 100% of the container‚Äôs width with an adaptive, scrollable height. You can set the widget to show as many or as few products as you like.   
![][image2]

## Helpful Guides

### üîπ WordPress Sites

If you edit your theme files directly

1. Log in to the WordPress Admin Dashboard.

2. In the left menu, go to:

    Appearance ‚Üí Theme File Editor (sometimes called ‚ÄúTheme Editor‚Äù).

3. In the right-hand sidebar, locate and select the file called header.php.

4. In the code editor, scroll until you see the closing \</head\> tag.

5. Just above the \</head\> line, paste in the following script:

\<script src="https://cdn.makemula.ai/js/mula.js" defer\>\</script\>

6. Click Update File to save changes.

7. Clear any site cache (if we‚Äôre using a caching plugin like WP Super Cache, W3 Total Cache, or similar).

8. Verify installation by opening the site in a browser, right-clicking ‚Üí View Source, and confirming the Mula script appears in the \<head\> section.

# KVP Reporting Setup

# **Mula KVP \+ Reporting (Google Ad Manager)**

This enables both teams to understand the impact and quantify the value driven by Mula, providing clear visibility into how they contribute to engagement and revenue across your site.

Setup takes under **3 minutes** and ensures accurate reporting aligned with your internal KPIs.

---

## **üß© Step 1: Create the Mula Key-Value**

1. **Open Google Ad Manager**

2. Navigate to **Inventory ‚Üí Key-values**

3. Click **‚ÄúNew key-value‚Äù**

4. Fill out the following:

   * **Name:** mula\_in\_view

   * **Display Name:** mula\_in\_view

   * **Value Type:** Predefined

   * **Reports on Values:** ‚úÖ *Include values in reporting*

5. Under **Targeting Values**, click **‚ÄúNew Values‚Äù**

6. Enter 1 in the new value field and click **Save**

7. Back on the list, check the box next to your new value (1) and click **Save** again

‚úÖ **Result:** You‚Äôll now see mula\_in\_view=1 available throughout GAM for reporting and targeting.
